href="angiuli-2024.xml"
addr="angiuli-2024"
title="Principles of Dependent Type Theory">notes on dependent types</fr:link>, I'm reminded that I've never really grasped the intuition behind substitutions in the calculus of substitutions.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta  \vdash  \gamma  : \Gamma ]]></fr:tex> denotes that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a substitution from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, and it sends terms from context <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> to context <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>. At a glance, this notation seems backwardsâ€”why not <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \vdash  \gamma  : \Delta ]]></fr:tex>?</fr:p><fr:p>In a more traditional presentation, a substitution is a mapping from variables to terms. Given a term <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \vdash  M : A]]></fr:tex>, we can substitute the variables of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> for some suitable new terms (of the right type) in another context <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>, yielding <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta  \vdash  M[\gamma ] : A]]></fr:tex>. Thus, one can think of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> as a list of terms in context <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> whose types are the ones in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>; this is captured by the notation <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta  \vdash  \gamma  : \Gamma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>